'''[[Ford Sigma engine|Zetec-SE (Sigma)]]''' (Used in [[Ford Fiesta|Fiesta Mk.4]], [[Ford Puma (sport compact)|Puma]], [[Ford Focus|Focus]])\n* 2000&ndash; '''[[Ford Duratorq engine|Duratorq]]'''&mdash;[[Diesel engine|Diesel]] (Europe: Used in [[Ford Mondeo|Mondeo Mk.3]], [[Ford Focus|Focus]], [[Ford Transit|Transit]], [[Ford Transit Connect|Transit Connect]], [[London Taxi|London Taxi TX1]] (from 2002 onwards))\n* 2000&ndash; '''[[Ford Duratec engine#Duratec 20|Duratec 8v/HE/20/23]]'''&mdash;(Duratec branded [[Mazda]]-engine used in [[Ford Mondeo|Mondeo Mk.3]], [[Ford Focus|Focus Mk.2]])\n* 2000&ndash;present '''[[Ford Power Stroke engine|Power Stroke 3.0]]'''<ref name=\"Owner's manual\">[http://www.ford.com.ar/ford2010/popup/ford_manual/manuales/manual_ranger.pdf Ford Ranger Owner's manual - p.192] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321085602/http://www.ford.com.ar/ford2010/popup/ford_manual/manuales/manual_ranger.pdf |date=2012-03-21 }} (in Spanish) - Accessed 03/08/2011</ref>&mdash;3.0&nbsp;L [[Diesel engine|Diesel]] ([[Brazil]]), Used in [[Ford Ranger (South America)#South American production|Ford Ranger (Argentina)]]\n* 2009&ndash;present '''[[Ford EcoBoost engine|EcoBoost]]'''&mdash;1.6&nbsp;L/2.0&nbsp;L [[Ford]] [[Ford Sigma engine|Sigma 1.6L]] and [[Mazda L engine|L 2.0L]]-engine with [[Direct Injection Spark Ignition]]\n* 2013&ndash;present '''[[Ford Ecoboost engine|Ecoboost]]'''&mdash;1.5 [[Ford]]\n* 2016&ndash;present [[EcoBlue]]&mdash;[[Diesel engine|Diesel]]\n\n==5 cylinder==\n* 2015\u2013present; The 3.2 is an I5 engine used in the Ford Transit, the Ford Ranger, Ford Everest, Mazda BT-50 and the Vivarail. For the North American-spec Transit, * the 3.2L Duratorq is modified to meet American and Canadian emissions standards and is branded as a Power Stroke engine. The 3.2 Power Stroke is rated 188 PS (138&nbsp;kW; 185&nbsp;hp) and 470 N\u22c5m (350&nbsp;lb\u22c5ft).[8]\n\n==6 cylinder==\nFord was late to offer a six-cylinder engine in their cars, only introducing a six in 1941 after the failure of the 1906 [[Ford Model K|Model K]]. The company relied on its famous [[Ford Flathead engine|Flathead V8]] for most models, only seriously producing six-cylinder engines in the 1960s. The company was also late with a [[V6 engine]], introducing a compact British V6 in 1967 but waiting until the 1980s to move their products to rely on V6 engines. The company has relied on six major V6 families ever since, the [[Ford Cologne V6 engine|Cologne/Taunus V6]], [[Ford Essex V6 engine (UK)|Essex V6]], [[Ford Essex V6 engine (Canadian)|Canadian Essex V6]], [[Ford Vulcan V6 engine|Vulcan V6]], [[Ford Mondeo engine|Mondeo V6]] and [[Ford Cyclone engine|Cyclone V6]]. The first three of these lines are no longer in production, leaving only the [[Ford Mondeo V6 engine|Mondeo]] and [[Ford Cyclone engine|Cyclone]] as the company's midrange engines.\n* 1906&ndash;1907 '''Model K straight-6'''\n* 1941&ndash;2016 '''[[Ford Straight-6 engine|Straight-6]]'''\n** 1941&ndash;1951 226&nbsp;[[Cubic inch|CID]] ''Flathead''\n** 1948&ndash;1953 254&nbsp;CID ''Flathead'' used in buses and two ton trucks\n** 1952&ndash;1964 [[Overhead valve|OHV]] (215, 223, 262) 215-223 used in car and non-HD pickups. 262 used in HD trucks only.\n[[Image:Ford 144cid six cylinder.jpg|thumb|right|180px|144&nbsp;CID [[straight-6]] in a 1964 [[Ford Falcon (North America)|Ford Falcon]]]]\n** 1960&ndash;1993 (Longer in [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Australia]]) 'Falcon Six' [[Overhead valve|OHV]] (144, 170, 200, 250) car usage.\n** 1964&ndash;1996 [[Overhead valve|OHV]] (240, 300, 4.9&nbsp;L) truck 6 built in [[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n** 1988&ndash;2002 [[Ford Australia]] [[SOHC]] [[Straight-six engine|I6]] [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Falcon]] engines\n*** 1988&ndash;1989 3.2&nbsp;L [[SOHC]]\n*** 1988&ndash;1992 3.9&nbsp;L [[SOHC]]\n*** 1992&ndash;2002 4.0&nbsp;L [[SOHC]]\n*** 1998&ndash;2002 4.0&nbsp;L [[SOHC]] VCT\n** 2002&ndash;2016 [[Ford Australia]] [[Ford Barra engine|Barra]] [[DOHC]] [[Straight-six engine|I6]] 4.0&nbsp;L engines\n* 1951&ndash;1966 '''[[Ford Zephyr engine|Zephyr 6]]'''&mdash;([[United Kingdom]])\n* 1966&ndash;1988 (2000 in South Africa) '''[[Ford Essex V6 engine (UK)|British Essex V6]]'''&mdash;60\u00b0 British V6 2.5/3.0/3.1/3.4&nbsp;L\n* 1964&ndash;2011 '''[[Ford Cologne V6 engine|Cologne/Taunus V6]]'''&mdash;1.8&ndash;4.0&nbsp;L [[pushrod]] and [[SOHC]] V6\n* 1982&ndash;2008 '''[[Ford Essex V6 engine (Canadian)|Canadian Essex V6]]'''&mdash;90\u00b0 V6, 3.8/3.9/4.2&nbsp;L models\n* 1986&ndash;1992 '''[[Ford Cologne V6 engine|Cologne/Ranger, Bronco II V6]] &mdash;''' 2.8/2.9/4.0OHV/4.0SOHC&nbsp;L\n* 1986&ndash;2007 '''[[Ford Vulcan engine|Vulcan V6]]'''&mdash;60\u00b0 [[pushrod]] V6 3.0&nbsp;L, originally designed for the [[Ford Taurus|Taurus]]\n* 1989&ndash;1995 '''[[Ford SHO V6 engine|SHO V6]]''' 3.0/3.2&nbsp;L [[DOHC]] V6\n* 1994&ndash;2012 '''[[Ford Duratec V6 engine|Mondeo V6]]''' aluminum 60\u00b0 [[DOHC]]\n** 1994&ndash;2002 '''[[Ford Duratec engine#Duratec 25 2|Duratec 25]]'''&mdash;2.5&nbsp;L\n** 1996&ndash;2012 '''[[Ford Duratec engine#Duratec 30|Duratec 30]]'''&mdash;3.0&nbsp;L\n** 2000&ndash;2011 '''[[Jaguar AJ-V6 engine|Jaguar AJ-V6]]'''&mdash;3.0&nbsp;L\n* 2003&ndash;present '''[[Ford Ecotorq engine|Ecotorq]]'''&mdash;7.3/9.0/12.7&nbsp;L [[Diesel engine|Diesel]]\n* 2004&ndash;present '''[[Ford AJD-V6/PSA DT17|AJD-V6]]'''&mdash;2.7&nbsp;L [[Diesel engine|Diesel]]\n* 2006&ndash;2016 '''[[Volvo SI6 engine|SI6]]'''&mdash;3.0/3.2&nbsp;L [[Straight-six engine|I6]] designed by [[Volvo Cars|Volvo]]{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n* 2006&ndash;present '''[[Ford Cyclone engine|Cyclone V6]]''' aluminum 60\u00b0 [[DOHC]]\n** 2018 '''[[Ford Cyclone engine#3.3 L|Duratec 33]]'''&mdash;3.3&nbsp;L\n** 2006&ndash;present '''[[Ford Duratec engine#Duratec 35|Duratec 35]]'''&mdash;3.5&nbsp;L\n** 2007&ndash;present '''[[Ford Duratec engine#Duratec 37|Duratec 37]]'''&mdash;3.7&nbsp;L\n*2009&ndash;present '''[[Ford EcoBoost engine|EcoBoost V6 engine]]\n** 2015&ndash;present '''[[Ford EcoBoost engine#2.7-L|EcoBoost]]'''&mdash;2.7&nbsp;L\n** 2016&ndash;present '''[[Ford EcoBoost engine#3.0-L|EcoBoost]]'''&mdash;3.0&nbsp;L\n** 2009&ndash;present '''[[Ford EcoBoost engine#3.5-L|EcoBoost]]'''&mdash;3.5&nbsp;L\n\n==8 cylinder==\n{{redirect2|Ford V-8|Ford V8|Ford's first mass-produced car with a V-8 engine|1932 Ford}}\nFord introduced the [[Ford flathead V8 engine|Flathead V8]] in their affordable [[1932 Ford|1932 Model 18]], becoming a performance leader for decades. In the 1950s, Ford introduced a three-tier approach to engines, with small, mid-sized, and larger engines aimed at different markets. All of Ford's mainstream V8 engines were replaced by the [[overhead cam]] [[Ford Modular engine|Modular family]] in the 1990s and the company introduced a new large architecture, the [[Ford Boss engine|Boss family]], for 2010.\n* 1920&ndash;1932 '''[[Lincoln Liberty engine|Lincoln 60 Degree Fork & Blade V8]]'''&mdash;({{convert|357.8|and|384.8|cid|L|1|abbr=on}})\n* 1932&ndash;1953 '''[[Ford flathead V8 engine|Flathead V8]]'''\n* 1940&ndash;1950 '''[[Ford GAA engine]]''', exclusively for [[armored fighting vehicle]] military use \n* 1952&ndash;1963 '''[[Lincoln Y-block V8 engine]]'''&mdash;[[big-block]] (317/341/368), HD truck (279/302/317/332)\n* 1954&ndash;1964 '''[[Ford Y-block engine|Y-block V8]]'''&mdash;[[small-block]] Ford/Mercury/Edsel (239/256/272/292/312)\n* 1958&ndash;1968 '''[[Ford MEL engine|MEL V8]]'''&mdash;big-block Mercury/Edsel/Lincoln (383/410/430/462)\n* 1958&ndash;1976 '''[[Ford FE engine|FE V8]]'''&mdash;[[Mid block|medium-block]] Ford/Edsel\n** 1958&ndash;1971 Generation I (332/352/360/361/390)\n** 1962&ndash;1973 Generation II (406/410/427/428)\n** 1965&ndash;1968 [[Ford 427 side oiler]]\n** FT truck (330/359/361/389/391)\n** 427 SOHC**\n* 1958&ndash;1981 '''[[Ford Super Duty engine|Super Duty truck engine]]'''&mdash;big-block (401/477/534)\n* 1962&ndash;2000 '''[[